Analyzing COVID-19 in the US and the Rest of the World¶

by Hira Mahmood

Introduction¶

The global COVID-19 pandemic has had, and continues to have, devastating effects across the the US and the rest of the world. However, countries are being effected on vastly different scales. Are there trends across these countries that help us predict COVID-19 severity? How about just within the US? This tutorial is going to walk through an analysis of COVID-19 US and global trends.

Data Collection¶

Setting Up¶

To start, we need to install the necessary Python packages.

In [1]:
import pandas as pd

Loading Data¶

We will be using the Data on COVID-19 complete dataset, maintained by Our World in Data. The dataset is compiled from various credible sources, including Johns Hopkins University and the European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control. Full information on the data, as well as the data itself, can be found at https://github.com/owid/covid-19-data/tree/master/public/data.

The data we will be using was retrieved on 5/11/2021, and contains data through 5/10/2021.

It's important to note that the data is subject to reporting from countries, and there is evidence that indicates some countries could be under-reporting COVID-19 cases or deaths: https://www.cfr.org/in-brief/how-much-are-countries-underreporting-covid-19-cases-and-deaths

Tidying the Data¶

The data has several NaN values through March 2020, presumably because this was when cases had just started to rise globally. To make things easier, we will only be looking at data from April 2020 onwards. We're choosing to do this because the remaining data is still large enough for us to analyze and find possible trends.

In [3]:
data = data[(data['date'] >= '2020-04-01')]
data.reset_index(inplace=True)
data = data.drop(['index'], axis=1)

There are some countries that are included in the dataset, but have no COVID-19 data (all column values are NaN). We will be dropping these.

The data contains many fields (59 columns!) but we are only interested in a smaller subset of them. For each country, along with data on covid, we will be looking at population, population density, GDP per capita, diabetes prevalence, life expectency, hospital beds per thousand, human development index, stringency index, and percent of population that is 65 and older. We will adjust the dataframe to only show these fields.

In [4]:
data = data[['iso_code','continent','location','date','total_cases','total_deaths','total_cases_per_million',
             'total_deaths_per_million','new_cases', 'new_cases_per_million','new_deaths','new_deaths_per_million', 'new_vaccinations',
             'new_vaccinations_smoothed','new_vaccinations_smoothed_per_million','stringency_index', 'people_vaccinated_per_hundred',
             'population','population_density','aged_65_older','gdp_per_capita','diabetes_prevalence', 'new_cases_smoothed_per_million',
             'new_deaths_smoothed_per_million', 'hospital_beds_per_thousand','life_expectancy','human_development_index']]

There are still NaN values values for new_vaccinations_smoothed and new_vaccinations_smoothed_per_million. Upon inspection we can see that these NaN values exist for the dates when there was no vaccine available, or readily available. So we will be replacing these NaN values for those columns with zeros. Here is the final cleaned-up dataframe.

In [5]:
data['new_vaccinations_smoothed'] = data['new_vaccinations_smoothed'].replace(np.nan, 0)
data['new_vaccinations_smoothed_per_million'] = data['new_vaccinations_smoothed_per_million'].replace(np.nan, 0)

Data Visualization and Analysis¶

Now that we have our data, we are going to create some visualizations to get an idea of what we are looking at and spot any potential trends.

We'll start off by creating a bar graph of total deaths caused by COVID-19 (as of May 1st 2021) for each country. We're going to pay more attention to deaths than cases, becuase we want to analyze the severity of COVID-19's impact.

In [6]:
#Dropping all rows with non-country locations so we can get a df of just the countries
index_names = data[data['location'] == 'Africa'].index
index_names = index_names.union((data[data['location'] == 'Asia'].index))
index_names = index_names.union((data[data['location'] == 'World'].index))
index_names = index_names.union((data[data['location'] == 'Europe'].index))
index_names = index_names.union((data[data['location'] == 'International'].index))
index_names = index_names.union((data[data['location'] == 'North America'].index))
index_names = index_names.union((data[data['location'] == 'Oceania'].index))
index_names = index_names.union((data[data['location'] == 'South America'].index))
index_names = index_names.union((data[data['location'] == 'European Union'].index))

countries_df = data.drop(index_names)

Okay, now that we have an idea of what the data looks like, let's try to find some trends. One of the most obviuous one seems to be that countries with a higher stringency index would tend to have less deaths per million. The dataset defines stringency index as a composite measure of how strictly a country has responded to COVID-19, on a scale of 0-100.

We'll create a scatterplot that looks at deaths per million vs mean stringency index for each country.

In [10]:
#getting the mean stringency index for each country
countries_df_avg = countries_df.groupby('location')['stringency_index'].mean().reset_index()
countries_death = countries_df.groupby('location')['new_deaths_pm'].sum().reset_index()
countries_df_avg['total_deaths_pm'] = countries_death['new_deaths_pm']
#plotting
countries_df_avg.plot(x='stringency_index', y='total_deaths_pm', kind='scatter',
                 title='Total Deaths by Mean Stringency Index')
Out[10]:
<AxesSubplot:title={'center':'Total Deaths by Mean Stringency Index'}, xlabel='stringency_index', ylabel='total_deaths_pm'>

There doesn't appear to be a negative correlation between stringency index and total deaths per million. Interestingly, the majority of the countries with high deaths have stringency indices above 50. One explanation for this may be that countries are enforcing stricter covid regulations as their deaths get higher.

Let's instead look at daily stringency index vs daily deaths over time for one country: the U.S. This may give us an idea of whether or not regulations are working.

It seems like we were right, at least for the US. The US seems to be adjusting their covid regulations strictness as needed: more deaths means it's time to increase regulations. However, it seems like deaths start decreasing shortly after regulations increased, which indicates the regulations work.

Hypothesis Testing¶

Now that we've done a general analysis of the data and found a trend between vaccinations and positive cases, let's do some hypothesis testing to see how strong the correlation is between these two variables.

First let's briefly go over what hypothesis testing is. Hypothsis testing provides us a way to test our results to see if they are satistically meaningful. If the results are meaningful, we are able to reject our null hypothesis. In this case, our null hypothesis would be that there is no relationship between total number of vaccinations and new daily cases. We are going to perform tests to see if we can reject this hypothsis.

We'll first perform spearman correlation tests to determine the significance of a monotonic relationship between total vaccinations and new COVID cases in each country. It's important to remember that we are only looking at a sample of countries that have been distributing the vaccine widely (we chose the US, the UK, the UAE, and Israel). So any correlations we find in this data can't necessarily be generalized to the rest of the world.

I will be replacing the NaN values with zero, becuase upon observation of the dataset, it seems like days with zero cases are sometimes represented as NaN. The NaN values are also rare, so it shouldn't affect our results anyways, becuase we have a high volume of non-NaN values.

In [17]:
#Spearman's Correlation test
for x in countries:
    x_country = vaccinated[(vaccinated['location'] == x)]
    data1 = x_country['cumsum_vacc_pm']
    data2 = x_country['new_cases_pm'].replace(np.nan, 0)
    r, p = spearmanr(data1, data2)
    print(x + ': r=%.3f, p=%.3f' % (r, p))

United States: r=-0.560, p=0.000
Israel: r=-0.918, p=0.000
United Kingdom: r=-0.952, p=0.000
United Arab Emirates: r=-0.883, p=0.000

The Pearson's correlation tests on the four countries gave us r values between -0.560 and -0.952. The r value varies between -1 and +1 with 0 implying no correlation. Correlations of -1 or +1 imply an exact monotonic relationship. So in this case, there is a high negative correlation for Israel, the UK, and the UAE. The US has a low negative correlation. The p-values are 0, which means that if we were able to find a reason behind a montonic relationship, we could reject the null hypothesis that there is no montonic correlation.

Now let's perform pearson's correlation tests. This checks for a linear relationship, rather than just a monotonic one.

In [18]:
#Pearson's Correlation test
for x in countries:
    x_country = vaccinated[(vaccinated['location'] == x)]
    data1 = x_country['cumsum_vacc_pm']
    data2 = x_country['new_cases_pm'].replace(np.nan, 0)
    r, p = pearsonr(data1, data2)
    print(x + ': r=%.3f, p=%.3f' % (r, p))

United States: r=-0.574, p=0.000
Israel: r=-0.919, p=0.000
United Kingdom: r=-0.859, p=0.000
United Arab Emirates: r=-0.841, p=0.000

Notice how the results match up with the scatterplots we previously created. The scatterplot 'Vaccinations vs Cases: United States' does not look linear, but rather polynominal, while the scatterplots for the other countries appear fairly linear.

While data like this (likely linear relationships with different r values), seems like it would be a good contender for a linear regression model with interaction terms for the countries, it would not be particularly useful in our case, given the context. The US's data is not strongly linear, and a linear regression for the other 3 countries (or even 4 countries with the US) would not be generalizable to other countries.

Conclusion¶

It's difficult to predict how badly COVID-19 would effect a country based off its quantifiable statistics and traits. Contrary to what we might think, there doesn't seem to be a set factor across countries that is able to make such a prediction. If there is, it could be one of the many factors that our dataset does not carry, such as the spread of mutative strains. As we discussed earlier, evidence from other studies points to a lack of consistent reporting, which would certainly affect our ability to make predictions or effectively analyze trends as well.

We did find that new case rates are declining in countries with easy access to vaccines. But the rate at which cases decline varies by country, suggesting that external factors are also at play.

I hope that you've found this tutorial useful in getting started with the data science pipeline. I also hope that you've gained some insight into the unpredictability of COVID severity and the effectiveness of mass vaccinations.
